WEBVTT

1
00:00:04.605 --> 00:00:07.655
This diagram shows the nature of interaction for a user

2
00:00:07.805 --> 00:00:10.535
with disabilities as they operate a digital interface.

3
00:00:11.455 --> 00:00:13.885
While the designer does not need to have a full command

4
00:00:13.885 --> 00:00:16.725
of this process, understanding what is happening

5
00:00:16.725 --> 00:00:19.205
behind the scenes provides context to the work

6
00:00:19.205 --> 00:00:22.685
of annotating designs with blue, blue lines at play.

7
00:00:22.685 --> 00:00:24.565
Here are the user with a disability,

8
00:00:25.995 --> 00:00:28.385
their assistive technology, like a screen reader,

9
00:00:28.445 --> 00:00:31.425
for example, the accessibility API,

10
00:00:31.725 --> 00:00:33.665
and the user interface of the application.

11
00:00:34.925 --> 00:00:36.225
The user with a disability

12
00:00:36.365 --> 00:00:38.745
who relies on assistive technology, like a screen reader,

13
00:00:39.335 --> 00:00:41.305
will initiate an interaction with the ui.

14
00:00:42.075 --> 00:00:43.985
Their assistive technology will reach out

15
00:00:43.985 --> 00:00:46.345
to the accessibility API, which is inherent

16
00:00:46.345 --> 00:00:47.865
to all platforms and surfaces.

17
00:00:48.535 --> 00:00:51.105
This interaction is where designers inform the process

18
00:00:51.685 --> 00:00:54.265
By providing the accessible name of a UI element,

19
00:00:54.405 --> 00:00:57.455
for example, the information is routed back

20
00:00:57.455 --> 00:00:59.575
to the user via their assistive technology.

21
00:01:00.565 --> 00:01:03.055
Without careful consideration of things like naming

22
00:01:03.735 --> 00:01:07.495
structure and keyboard focus, path management, this aspect

23
00:01:07.495 --> 00:01:09.935
of the user experience may be of low quality

24
00:01:10.315 --> 00:01:11.735
and often can cause human harm.

25
00:01:12.525 --> 00:01:15.335
Blue line annotations seek to alleviate these problems

26
00:01:15.595 --> 00:01:17.895
by considering accessibility as a factor

27
00:01:17.895 --> 00:01:19.495
of the overall user experience.

28
00:01:19.985 --> 00:01:21.295
Click next to proceed.

29
00:01:23.605 --> 00:01:26.455
Assistive technologies include things like screen readers,

30
00:01:26.755 --> 00:01:29.055
speech input, software keyboards,

31
00:01:29.055 --> 00:01:30.935
and keyboard alternatives, and much more.

32
00:01:32.165 --> 00:01:34.495
This training focuses on the assistive technologies

33
00:01:34.915 --> 00:01:36.775
of screen readers, speech input,

34
00:01:37.035 --> 00:01:39.415
and keyboards, as they're the most impacted

35
00:01:39.435 --> 00:01:40.935
by blue line annotations.

36
00:01:41.975 --> 00:01:44.155
Screen readers are primarily utilized

37
00:01:44.215 --> 00:01:46.595
by people without the ability to see the interface

38
00:01:46.935 --> 00:01:48.235
and instead listen to it.

39
00:01:49.335 --> 00:01:50.925
These users rely on a keyboard

40
00:01:51.385 --> 00:01:53.485
and speech input rather than using a mouse.

41
00:01:54.435 --> 00:01:56.165
This software reads aloud content

42
00:01:56.505 --> 00:01:59.565
and the user interface via a synthesized speech output

43
00:02:00.025 --> 00:02:04.525
and relies on keyboard or gesture to operate keyboard only.

44
00:02:04.625 --> 00:02:07.125
And keyboard alternatives are primarily for users

45
00:02:07.265 --> 00:02:09.845
who cannot rely on a mouse to operate the interface.

46
00:02:10.745 --> 00:02:11.885
All functionality needs

47
00:02:11.885 --> 00:02:14.805
to be made available via a single action like a key press

48
00:02:15.385 --> 00:02:17.125
or manipulating a switch device.

49
00:02:18.465 --> 00:02:21.565
Speech input is utilized primarily by people with physical

50
00:02:21.565 --> 00:02:22.565
or motor impairments

51
00:02:22.565 --> 00:02:25.125
that prevent them from using a pointing device like a mouse.

52
00:02:26.105 --> 00:02:29.565
By considering how the interface functions via speech output

53
00:02:29.745 --> 00:02:31.805
and speech input, as well as

54
00:02:31.805 --> 00:02:33.965
how the interface functions without the use

55
00:02:33.965 --> 00:02:37.165
of a pointing device, the designer helps ensure the

56
00:02:37.165 --> 00:02:38.965
interface is usable by people

57
00:02:38.965 --> 00:02:40.525
with a wide spectrum of abilities.

58
00:02:42.065 --> 00:02:45.045
The screen reader is by far the assistive technology

59
00:02:45.435 --> 00:02:47.325
that designers will spend the most time

60
00:02:47.785 --> 00:02:49.605
and effort and annotating for.

61
00:02:50.585 --> 00:02:55.045
The annotation types of accessible name landmarks, headings,

62
00:02:55.185 --> 00:02:58.325
and keyboard focus and tab order all have a net effect

63
00:02:58.345 --> 00:02:59.490
on the screen reader user.

64
00:03:00.465 --> 00:03:01.925
If we take a simple example

65
00:03:02.065 --> 00:03:05.285
of an action only button in spectrum, we can see

66
00:03:05.285 --> 00:03:06.405
that the designer needs

67
00:03:06.405 --> 00:03:08.405
to annotate the accessible name as print.

68
00:03:09.305 --> 00:03:11.125
The engineer then codes that properly

69
00:03:11.125 --> 00:03:12.205
with the accessible name.

70
00:03:13.145 --> 00:03:15.005
The accessible name is now available

71
00:03:15.065 --> 00:03:16.565
to the accessibility API.

72
00:03:17.185 --> 00:03:19.565
So the screen reader could announce print

73
00:03:19.585 --> 00:03:21.285
button to the screen reader.

74
00:03:21.315 --> 00:03:25.525
User designers don't need to use the words aria label

75
00:03:25.665 --> 00:03:27.005
and their design annotations.

76
00:03:27.985 --> 00:03:29.485
The designer here only needs

77
00:03:29.485 --> 00:03:31.805
to consider the oral user experience.

78
00:03:33.005 --> 00:03:34.195
Click next to proceed.
